1. Introduction
Handwritten character recognition is a key application of deep learning, used in areas such as
automated document processing, postal code reading, and bank cheque digitization. This project
implements a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to recognize handwritten digits using the
MNIST dataset, demonstrating efficient and accurate character recognition. 2. Objective
The objective of this task is to identify handwritten characters or digits by applying image
processing and deep learning techniques, specifically through a CNN architecture. 3. Dataset
MNIST (Modified National Institute of Standards and Technology) dataset was utilized:
Feature Description
Total Images 70,000
Training Set 60,000
Testing Set 10,000
Image Size 28 × 28 grayscale
Classes 10 digits (0–9)
The dataset was loaded using TensorFlow/Keras utilities and preprocessed for CNN input. 4. Methodology
4.1Data Preprocessing
4.2Normalized pixel values from 0–255 to 0–1

 Reshaped images to fit CNN input format (28×28×1)
4.2 Model Architecture
The CNN model consists of:
1. Convolutional Layer – Extracts features using ReLU activation
2. MaxPooling Layer – Reduces spatial dimensions
3. Flatten Layer – Converts 2D data into 1D vector
4. Dense Layer – Fully connected layer for learning
5. Output Layer – Softmax activation for classification
4.3 Model Training
 Optimizer: Adam
 Loss Function: Sparse Categorical Crossentropy
 Epochs: 5
 Validation Data: Test set (10,000 images)
5. Results
Metric Value
Training Accuracy 99.58%
Validation Accuracy 99.05%
Training Loss 0.0122
Validation Loss 0.0293
The model achieved high accuracy, confirming effective learning. Training curves show steady
improvement across epochs. 6. Conclusion
This task successfully demonstrates handwritten digit recognition using a CNN.
 The model achieved high accuracy on MNIST digits.  The project can be extended to recognize alphabets using the EMNIST dataset or full
words using CRNN models.  This task fulfills all objectives of Task 3: Handwritten Character Recognition under
the CodeAlpha internship. 7. References
